"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934397","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-06","<p>We understand the importance of broadcast licensing arrangements for the sector. As set out by the Prime Minister’s Mansion House Speech, we are seeking to strike a bespoke deal with the EU which would allow for mutual recognition of cross-border broadcasting post EU Exit. However, the final outcome will depend on exit negotiations. Our negotiating teams will continue to work at pace to ensure these are finalised.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to working with the broadcasting sector to understand their needs and concerns, and will continue focussing on negotiating the right future relationship with the EU over the coming months.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-07-06T09:37:16.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934397/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934397/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-03","Broadcasting: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent progress he has made on negotiating a deal with the EU on broadcast licensing.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","160117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934398","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-11","<p>The British Government monitors closely the number of migrants who cross the Mediterranean to Europe, or attempt this dangerous crossing, including via the Central Mediterranean route from Libya to Italy. The International Organisation for Migration's (IOM) publication 'Migration Flows to Europe – Quarterly Review, Q1 2018' states that there were 497 fatalities across the three Mediterranean routes (Central Route, Western Route from Morocco to Spain and Eastern Route from Turkey to Greece) from January to March 2018 compared with 803 for the same period last year. Despite this reduction, this shows the ongoing need to tackle the challenge of illegal migration and its consequences. The British Government will continue to engage proactively with the EU and internationally in pursuit of a whole of route approach to tacking this challenge.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-07-11T14:00:41.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934398/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934398/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-03","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of migrants departing from the Libyan coast who have drowned in the last two months.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","160165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934399","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-11","<p>​The British Government recognises the value of search and rescue operations undertaken by Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) in the Mediterranean but does not provide financial or diplomatic support. Since May 2015, UK naval and Border Force assets under EU Operation Sophia and Frontex operations have rescued over 31,000 people in the central Mediterranean and Aegean.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-07-11T14:03:32.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934399/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934399/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-03","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what (a) financial and (b) diplomatic support the Government is offering to humanitarian rescue missions offering help to migrants departing the Libyan coast.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","160166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934401","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>As is normal practice, Service medical records are retained for nuclear test participants, but these individual military medical records are not held centrally.</p><p>Records held by the Atomic Weapons Establishment include those related to the single use film badges, which, as is normal practice, were destroyed after their measurements were recorded. In some cases measurements were not taken because the badges were lost or damaged in situ. Where measurements were found to align with background levels readings were, in some cases, not retained.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","160134 ; 160135","2018-07-11T14:23:20.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934401/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934401/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Veterans: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government has retained records of the health monitoring carried out during UK nuclear tests in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934402","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>As is normal practice, Service medical records are retained for nuclear test participants, but these individual military medical records are not held centrally.</p><p>Records held by the Atomic Weapons Establishment include those related to the single use film badges, which, as is normal practice, were destroyed after their measurements were recorded. In some cases measurements were not taken because the badges were lost or damaged in situ. Where measurements were found to align with background levels readings were, in some cases, not retained.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","160133 ; 160135","2018-07-11T14:23:20.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934402/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934402/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Veterans: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the fate of the film badges worn by veterans who were present during the British nuclear tests carried out in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934403","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>As is normal practice, Service medical records are retained for nuclear test participants, but these individual military medical records are not held centrally.</p><p>Records held by the Atomic Weapons Establishment include those related to the single use film badges, which, as is normal practice, were destroyed after their measurements were recorded. In some cases measurements were not taken because the badges were lost or damaged in situ. Where measurements were found to align with background levels readings were, in some cases, not retained.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","160133 ; 160134","2018-07-11T14:23:21.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934403/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934403/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Veterans: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the radiation readings measured by the film badges worn by veterans during the nuclear tests carried out in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934404","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>Alpha radiation was not routinely measured to monitor the environment because measuring beta and gamma radiation was more efficient.</p><p>Alpha monitoring equipment was held at Christmas Island as a contingency in the event of an accident, but was never required.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-07-11T14:24:29.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934404/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934404/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Veterans: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the alpha radiation contamination on Christmas Island during the UK nuclear tests in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934405","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>Information is held which confirms that regulations were in place to ensure that protection and safety information was given by the officer responsible to all personnel involved in each task. This included subjects such as basic training in nuclear weapon effect and health physics for all ranks, personal protection and issue and use of protective clothing and dosemeters and training in radiological safety.</p><p>The tests took place over or off an uninhabited part of Christmas Island. Inhabitants of other parts of the island would have been protected by generic safety precautions such as designated restricted areas.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","160138 ; 160141","2018-07-11T16:56:11.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934405/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934405/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Veterans: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the (a) protection and (b) safety training that was provided to service personnel who collected monitoring equipment and assessed bomb damage after the UK nuclear tests in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934406","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-11","<p>Information is held which confirms that regulations were in place to ensure that protection and safety information was given by the officer responsible to all personnel involved in each task. This included subjects such as basic training in nuclear weapon effect and health physics for all ranks, personal protection and issue and use of protective clothing and dosemeters and training in radiological safety.</p><p>The tests took place over or off an uninhabited part of Christmas Island. Inhabitants of other parts of the island would have been protected by generic safety precautions such as designated restricted areas.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","160137 ; 160141","2018-07-11T16:56:11.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934406/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/934406/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-03","Christmas Island: Radiation Exposure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the (a) protection and (b) safety training that was provided to Christmas Island inhabitants during the nuclear tests on that island in the 1950s and 1960s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","160138"
